1303","1246":"1246","1312":"1312","1267":"1267","1289":"1289","1321":"1321","1310":"1310","1299":"1299","about 1299":"circa 1299","about 1310":"circa 1310","after 1312":"na 1312","Redbourn, Hertfordshire, England, United Kingdom":"Redbourn, Hertfordshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Wheathampstead, Hertfordshire, England, United Kingdom":"Wheathampstead, Hertfordshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Redbourn, Hertfordshire, England":"Redbourn, Hertfordshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Essex, England, United Kingdom":"Essex, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1267–1321":"1267–1321","1252–Male":"1252–Deceased","1267–Female":"1267–Deceased","–1370":"–1370","1289–1312":"1289–1312","1299–1360":"1299–1360","1310–Male":"1310–Deceased","1246–1303":"1246–1303","1252":"1252","1360":"1360","1370":"1370","abt 1289":"about 1289","1303":"1303","1246":"1246","1312":"1312","1267":"1267","1289":"1289","1321":"1321","1310":"1310","1299":"1299","about 1299":"about 1299","about 1310":"about 1310","after 1312":"after 1312","Redbourn, Hertfordshire, England, United Kingdom":"Redbourn, Hertfordshire, England, United Kingdom","Wheathampstead, Hertfordshire, England, United Kingdom":"Wheathampstead, Hertfordshire, England, United Kingdom","Redbourn, Hertfordshire, England":"Redbourn, Hertfordshire, England, United Kingdom","Essex, England, United Kingdom":"Essex, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Inge","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from the district of <i>Ing</i> (Essex), now represented by the placenames <i>Ingrave</i>, <i>Ingatestone</i>, <i>Fryerning</i>, <i>Margaretting</i>, and <i>Mountnessing</i>, as well as earlier alternative names of Fouchers (in East Hornden) and Buttsbury. The placename means ‘people of the district’, from Old English <i>gē</i> ‘district, region’ + the Old English groupname suffix <i>-ingas</i>.","English: from Middle English <i>Inge</i>, itself either from the Old Norse female personal name <i>Inga</i> (a pet form of such names as <i>Ingi(v)aldr</i>), or from the Scandinavian male personal name <i>Inge</i> (a pet form of such names as <i>Ingiríthr</i>), or the Anglo-Saxon form of such a name, <i>Inga</i>. Unless there are other indications of gender, the two sources cannot be distinguished.","German: probably from the ancient Germanic female personal name <i>Inga</i>."],"variants":[{"name":"Ing","meanings":["English (Buckinghamshire and Middlesex): variant of   Inge  .","Jewish (eastern Ashkenazic): nickname from Yiddish <i>ing</i> ‘young’.","Chinese: alternative Cantonese form of the surnames 應, 嬴, and 英, see   Ying   1-3."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Sir William Inge was born in 1267, in Redbourn, Hertfordshire, England, United Kingdom as the son of Robert Inge. He married Isolda de Seyntpiere. He died in 1321, in Wheathampstead, Hertfordshire, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 54."},"et":{"1267–1321":"1267–1321","1252–Male":"1252–Surnud","1267–Female":"1267–Surnud","–1370":"–1370","1289–1312":"1289–1312","1299–1360":"1299–1360","1310–Male":"1310–Surnud","1246–1303":"1246–1303","1252":"1252","1360":"1360","1370":"1370","abt 1289":"umbes